1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,799
Let us put what you have learned into practice with a scenario.

2
00:00:04,799 --> 00:00:08,000
Marcus is a 45-year-old man who is Deaf.

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:11,599
He communicates primarily in American Sign Language — ASL.

4
00:00:11,599 --> 00:00:17,600
He arrives at the outpatient reception desk at a UHN clinic for a pre-surgical consultation.

5
00:00:17,600 --> 00:00:29,600
He holds up his phone, which shows a text message that reads: "I need a sign language interpreter for my appointment."

The receptionist, Lin, has not encountered this situation before.

6
00:00:29,600 --> 00:00:32,399
She is not sure what to do.

7
00:00:32,399 --> 00:00:34,799
The appointment is in 20 minutes.

8
00:00:34,799 --> 00:00:37,199
There is no interpreter on site.

9
00:00:37,199 --> 00:00:39,199
Now it is your turn.

10
00:00:39,199 --> 00:00:41,599
Think about the Accessibility Decision Path.

11
00:00:41,599 --> 00:00:43,199
What should Lin do?

12
00:00:43,199 --> 00:00:45,999
You will see three options on screen.

13
00:00:45,999 --> 00:00:49,999
Choose the one that best reflects an accessible, dignity-centred response.

14
00:00:49,999 --> 00:00:55,999
After you choose, you will receive feedback explaining the strengths and limitations of each option.

15
00:00:55,999 --> 00:00:57,499
Take your time.

16
00:00:57,499 --> 00:01:03,099
There is no penalty for choosing an imperfect answer — this is about learning.
